    { label: "Concessions", value: "None on the Watch Hill side" },
    { label: "Facilities", value: "None — bring everything" },
  ],
  introParagraphs: [
    "East Beach is the locals' beach. It runs from the eastern edge of Watch Hill village for about two miles along the Atlantic, connecting directly to Misquamicut State Beach at its eastern end. Same sand, same water, same coastline — but with a fraction of the crowds of Misquamicut, no concessions, no lifeguards on the Watch Hill end, and access restrictions that keep most tourists away.",
    "The reason East Beach works as a quieter alternative is purely structural. The Watch Hill Fire District restricts parking near the beach access points to residents and registered hotel guests during summer months. There's no public lot. Most tourists who arrive in Watch Hill village in summer don't realize East Beach exists — they head straight to Bay Street, the carousel, or drive five minutes east to Misquamicut. Those who know East Beach is here either are local, are staying at Ocean House or Watch Hill Inn, or have figured out the walk-in trick from Misquamicut.",
    "The beach itself is identical in quality to Misquamicut — wide, fine, white sand, gentle Atlantic surf, ocean temperatures climbing into the high 60s by July and topping out around 70°F in August. Napatree Point is a 10-minute walk west; the Misquamicut amusement strip is a 25-minute walk east. East Beach sits quietly between them.",
  ],
  tips: [
    {
      label: "How to actually get on the beach",
      body: "<strong>If you're staying at Ocean House, Weekapaug Inn, or Watch Hill Inn:</strong> the hotel handles beach access through their Ocean House Collection beach service, including cabanas at Ocean House's private beach section. <strong>If you're staying at a Watch Hill rental:</strong> ask the owner about the Fire District sticker or guest pass — many rentals include one. <strong>If you're a day-tripper:</strong> park at Misquamicut State Beach ($20–$30) and walk west along the shoreline — it's about 20 minutes to reach the Watch Hill section, and you can walk as far as Napatree Point if you want.",
    },
    {
      label: "The Misquamicut walk-in is the secret",
      body: "Most day visitors don't realize you can park at Misquamicut and walk west on the beach into the Watch Hill section. The walk is on hard sand at low tide and softer sand at high tide — go in the morning when the tide is favorable. Once you're past the Misquamicut concession area and the lifeguard stations, the crowds thin dramatically. Within 15 minutes of walking you're on what feels like a private beach.",
    },
    {
      label: "What to bring",
      body: "Everything. There are no concessions, no restrooms, no umbrellas for rent, no chair service on the Watch Hill end. Pack: water (lots in summer), sunscreen, a beach umbrella or shade, snacks, towels, a small cooler. If you're walking in from Misquamicut, factor the carry into your packing — keep it light.",
    },
    {
      label: "No lifeguards on the Watch Hill end",
      body: "Lifeguards are only stationed at the Misquamicut State Beach section. Swimming on the Watch Hill end is at your own risk. The surf is generally gentle but rip currents can form on outgoing tides. Watch the conditions, swim near other people, and don't go in alone if the waves look bigger than usual.",
    },
    {
      label: "Combine with Napatree Point",
      body: "If you're on East Beach for half a day, the natural pairing is the Napatree Point walk to the west. From the Watch Hill end of East Beach, walk west along the shoreline and around the harbor — you'll connect to Napatree's barrier peninsula and the WWI Fort Mansfield ruins at the far end. The full combined walk (beach + Napatree) is about 4 miles and takes 2–3 hours. Bring a change of clothes if you want to swim partway through.",
    },
  ],
